  ITEP-TH-03/03

 EMPG-03-01
 
 

 
We present a formula for a classical -matrix
of an integrable system obtained by Hamiltonian reduction 
of some free field theories using pure gauge symmetries.
The framework of the reduction
is restricted only by the assumption that
the respective gauge transformations are Lie group
ones. Our formula is in terms of Dirac brackets, and some
new observations on these brackets are made. We apply our method to derive
a classical -matrix for the elliptic Calogero-Moser system
with spin starting from the Higgs bundle over an elliptic curve with
marked points.
In the paper we also derive a classical Feigin-Odesskii algebra
by a Poisson reduction of some modification of the Higgs
bundle over an elliptic curve.
This allows us to include integrable lattice models in a 
Hitchin type construction.


Introduction 
A classical -matrix structure is an important tool for investigating
integrable systems. It encodes the
Hamiltonian
structure of the Lax equation, provides the involution of integrals of motion,
and gives a natural framework for quantizing integrable systems in a
quantum group theoretic setting.

The aim of this paper is severalfold.
First, we present a formula
for the classical -matrices of integrable systems, derived
in the framework of Dirac's Hamiltonian reduction for systems
involving only gauge transformations.  In the process we shall derive
new results describing the Dirac brackets.  As an application of our
general formula we shall calculate a classical -matrix for the 
elliptic Calogero-Moser system with spin.
Following the workswe start from the Higgs bundle over an elliptic curve with a marked
point. This is a free theory with a trivial -matrix. After the
Dirac procedure we come to the desired -matrix.
Finally we derive the classical Feigin-Odesskii algebrain the similar fashion. Here the corresponding unreduced space is 
similar to the cotangent bundle of the centrally extended loop group 
.
The Poisson structure on this space is a particular example of
a general construction proposed in.
In this way we derive the corresponding quadratic Poisson algebra
using the Hitchin approach. Thus we have managed to include 
integrable lattice models in the general Hitchin construction.

Our work is motivated by the papers
 where the authors use a gauge
invariant extension of Lax matrices to derive classical
-matrices for the Toda
chain, and for the trigonometric and
elliptic (spin zero) Calogero-Moser systems.
In the first paperthe Hamiltonian reduction is considered on the cotangent
bundle to a finite dimensional Lie group,
while in the second paper the construction is
generalised to the case of the central extension
of the loop group.
In this context the paper also
warrants mention. There
the authors consider a special case
of Poisson reduction on Poisson-Lie groupoids in
order to obtain new examples of the class
of dynamical -matrices defined by
Etingof and Varchenko.


In our paper we propose a very general framework for
Hamiltonian reduction by pure gauge symmetries
that allows one to derive a classical -matrix.
This framework is based on rather general assumptions:
essentially that the first class constraints generate
the adjoint action of some Lie algebra on a (Lie algebra valued) function on
the unreduced space, which in turn reduces
to the Lax equation, and that the Poisson brackets between
these elements is already cast into -matrix form.

The organisation of the paper is as follows.
In the second section we outline
the general framework of the
Hamiltonian reduction which allows us to
derive -matrices for integrable
systems. In the third section we discuss the Dirac brackets and the -matrices
more generally, relating each of these to generalized inverses. This sheds
some new light on Dirac's brackets. The fourth section consists of our
first example, where
we apply our method to derive the classical -matrix
structure for the elliptic Calogero-Moser system
with spin using
its C ech-like Hitchin description.
The fifth section
is devoted to the derivation of the
classical Feigin-Odesskii algebra from some free field theory.
This theory is a modification of the Higgs bundle related to the
holomorphic -bundle of degree one over an
elliptic curve. Instead of a Higgs field that takes values in 
the endomorphisms of the bundle we consider the field of 
automorphisms of the bundle.
It is a Poisson manifold and
we show that the elliptic Belavin-Drinfeld -matrixis naturally obtained in the context of such a reduction.
In the concluding section we discuss a possible generalisation 
of our reduction technique to Hitchin systems on 
curves of higher genus. An Appendix is devoted to
the special elliptic functions we use.

Throughout the paper we use standard notations from 
quantum group theory and integrable systems to express the
Poisson brackets between entries of matrices.
Thus, for example, the -matrix equation cast as
 
