We will specify this ambiguity in due course.

The Formal R-Matrix via Hamiltonian Reduction 
In this section we show that if a classical integrable system
is obtained by a Hamiltonian reduction involving purely gauge symmetries,
and so corresponding first class constraints, then
the system admits a canonical -matrix.
The word "formal" in the title of the section stresses the fact that
in many interesting cases the reduction is performed in the context
of a field theory, and consequently for
such systems the formula for the -matrix must be properly
defined.

Our approach makes three quite general assumptions regarding the Hamiltonian reduction
that allows us to calculate the -matrix.
These are:
 

There exists an element , which upon reduction becomes
the Lax matrix, and this takes values in some Lie algebra .

The gauge transformations
of  can be represented as
 
where  is assumed to take values in the Lie group 
corresponding to the Lie algebra .

The  Poisson brackets between the
"entries" of the element  in the unreduced space have been cast
into the -matrix form before reduction.



The first two assumptions are quite natural if we
wish to obtain an integrable system together
with its Lax representation. The second assumption implies that
the Poisson brackets between the first class constraints
