where  is a basis of the Lie algebra of gauge
transformations (which may be a subalgebra of ).
The third assumption is more elaborate.
It means that there exists a classical
-matrix , defining the
Poisson brackets in the total or unreduced space between the "entries" of

 

Our first calculation below shows how the initial
-matrix  produces, under reduction, the desired classical
-matrix of the integrable system. One may feel that we have
simply transferred the problem of constructing an -matrix for
a reduced system to one of constructing an -matrix for an unreduced
system. In practice constructing the latter -matrix is often easier,
but we will deal with the construction of  in the next section.

