In section four we apply the method outlined here to derive the 
classical -matrix for the elliptic Calogero-Moser system with spin.
Before so doing however, let us return to the question of ,
and place our construction in a somewhat broader context.

Dirac Brackets, Generalized Inverses and R-Matrices 
Our assumptions have a priori  assumed the existence of an -matrix
 for the unreduced system.
In many examples such unreduced -matrices are easy to construct: when the
unreduced matrices  depend only on half of the phase space variables, such as the
momenta, then for example  is a possible solution.
Such however is not always the case, and in this section we shall discuss
the issue of the existence of .
This will enable us both to place our Dirac Bracket construction
in a wider context and to elaborate on the remarks of concerning
this reduction procedure. For concreteness we shall phrase our discussion
in the language of finite dimensional matrices (as we did in the previous
section).

The construction of -matrices is essentially an algebraic operation.
This algebraic nature was clarified in where a necessary and
sufficient condition was given for the existence of an -matrix
based upon the fundamental Poisson brackets of the Lax matrix
(here ). The novel part of this investigation was the use of
generalized inverses (and the construction thereof for generic elements
of the adjoint representation of a Lie algebra ).
We shall recall these notions in our present setting, relating them
to Dirac brackets. In so doing we will arrive at some new results pertaining
to Dirac brackets.

We begin with generalized inverses.
